formula_129

=== Conformal mappings in higher dimensions ===
Let Ω be an open set in the Euclidean space formula_130. The equation for an orientation-preserving mapping formula_131 to be a conformal mapping (that is, angle-preserving) is that
formula_132

where &quot;Df&quot; is the Jacobian matrix, with transpose formula_133, and &quot;I&quot; denotes the identity matrix. For , this system is equivalent to the standard Cauchy–Riemann equations of complex variables, and the solutions are holomorphic functions. In dimension , this is still sometimes called the Cauchy–Riemann system, and Liouville&#x27;s theorem implies, under suitable smoothness assumptions, that any such mapping is a Möbius transformation.

=== Lie pseudogroups ===
One might seek to generalize the Cauchy-Riemann equations instead by asking more generally when are the solutions of a system of PDEs closed under composition. The theory of Lie Pseudogroups addresses these kinds of questions.

